PORTUGUESE-based strikers Luther Singh and Liam Jordan will carry Mzansi&rsquo;s hopes. Under-20 Fifa Youth World Cup on in South Korea their shoulders.&nbsp;Singh won the Golden Boot Award in his last two tournaments with Amajita, the CAF U-20 African Nations Cup in Zambia early this year and the Cosafa Championships in Rustenburg, North West, in December.&nbsp;The player from Noordgesig, south of Joburg, says he has more to offer.&nbsp;But he feels Amajita will have to work as a team if the junior national side intend doing well in the World Cup.&nbsp;Amajita are already in South Korea for the competition, due to kick-off on Saturday to 11 June.&nbsp;The U-20 side is in Group D, alongside Japan, Italy and Uruguay.&nbsp;According to Singh, Amajita intend to make the finals despite being in a tough group.&nbsp;Said Singh: &ldquo;We know what&rsquo;s expected from us and we&rsquo;ll give it our best shot. We&rsquo;ll take it one game at a time. Our group is not easy, but we&rsquo;d love to pass the group stages and the last 16.&nbsp;&ldquo;I&rsquo;m used to the European teams&rsquo; style of play, so I&rsquo;ll just share the knowledge with my team-mates.&nbsp;&ldquo;We&rsquo;ll also make sure we do our best because the opportunity to play in a World Cup comes once every so often.&rdquo;&nbsp;Singh said he was aware of what he had done for the team, and wanted to continue doing that without putting himself under pressure.&nbsp;&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t want to put myself and the team under pressure. We aim to enjoy ourselves while doing the work. Working as a team will always be a key for us to stay longer in the tournament.&rdquo;&nbsp;Amajita left without Phakamani Mahlambi, Reeve Frosler of Bidvest Wits and SuperSport United&rsquo;s Teboho Mokoena, who&rsquo;ll join the team in Korea. This will be Amajita&rsquo;s third appearance at a World Cup. Their last appearance was in 2009 in Egypt, where they were knocked out in the group stages after winning one match, drawing one and losing the other.&nbsp;